==English==
{{wp}}

===Etymology===
From {{compound|en|bat|-s-|-man}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈbætsmən/}}
* {{audio|en|en-au-batsman.ogg|a=AU}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|batsmen}}

# {{lb|en|cricket}} A [[player]] of the [[batting]] [[side]] now on the [[field]].
# {{lb|en|cricket}} The [[player]] now [[receiving]] [[strike]]; the [[striker]].
#* {{quote-web|en|author=w:Julia Price|title=Julia's Ashes Diary 2001 |work=Women's Cricket in Australia -Ashes Tour 2001|url=http://www.southernstars.org.au/ukdiary2001.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322193830/http://www.southernstars.org.au/ukdiary2001.htm|archivedate=22 March 2015|publisher=southernstars.org|date=19 June 2001|accessdate=22 March 2015|passage=The '''batsman''', Kathryn Leng, (who has played for quite a few years for England) asked the umpire dumbfounded if Charlie was going to bowl with a helmet on.}}
# {{lb|en|cricket}} Any player selected for his or her [[team]] principally to [[bat]], as opposed to a [[bowler]].
# {{lb|en|baseball|now rare}} A [[hitter]].
# {{lb|en|aviation|historical}} An [[officer]] who used a pair of hand-held bats to [[signal]] to [[aircraft]] as they came in to land on the [[flight deck]].

====Usage notes====
* The term batsman is applied to both male and female cricketers; {{m|en|batswoman}} is much rarer.
* In baseball, ''batsman'' is rarely used outside of the phrase 'hit batsman'.

====Synonyms====
